(2431, 'jpsq_sync-1491198417.672929-661880-3', 'a:5:{i:0;s:14:\"wp_insert_post\";i:1;a:3:{i:0;i:147;i:1;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:147;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"5\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-03 05:46:57\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"0000-00-00 00:00:00\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:1931:\"NASA’s Solar Probe Plus will enter the sun’s corona and measure the full force of supersonic solar particles and radiation with a Faraday cup developed by the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory and Draper.\n\nWhen clouds of high-speed charged particles come racing off the sun, they can bathe spacecraft, astronauts and planetary surfaces in damaging radiation. Understanding why the sun occasionally emits these high-energy particles can help scientists predict space weather. Knowing when solar energetic particles may hit Earth can help people on the planet take precautions.\n\nNASA’s Solar Probe Plus spacecraft\nNASA’s Solar Probe Plus spacecraft, will make 24 solar flybys over nearly seven years, setting a new record for the fastest moving man-made object as it zips 37.6 million kilometers closer to the sun than any spacecraft that has ever studied this star, and be exposed to temperatures exceeding 2500 degrees Fahrenheit.\n\nNASA’s Solar Probe Plus — the first mission that will fly into the sun’s upper atmosphere and “touch” the sun — will collect data on the mechanisms that heat the corona and accelerate the solar wind, a constant flow of charged particles from the sun. These are two processes with fundamental roles in the complex interconnected system linking the sun and near-Earth space—a system that can drive changes in our space weather and impact our satellites.\n\nVelocity and Direction\n\nTo capture the velocity and direction of the positively-charged particles,The Faraday cup, which is capable of measuring the full force of supersonic solar particles and radiation, is one of only two instruments riding outside the protective sunshield of NASA’s Solar Probe Plus. The challenge will be to capture the data while operating at extreme temperatures on the fastest moving manmade spacecraft ever created—it will achieve a velocity of close to 200 km/sec—and do it with accuracy.\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:63:\"NASA’s Solar Probe Plus  will fly into sun\'s upper atmosphere\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:5:\"draft\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:4:\"open\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:4:\"open\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-04-03 05:46:57\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-03 05:46:57\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:38:\"http://successfulindia.aypt.in/blog/?p=147\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"post\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:2;b:1;}i:2;i:5;i:3;d:1491198417.6729218959808349609375;i:4;b:0;}', 'no'),
