(57, 1, '2017-01-09 05:12:31', '2017-01-09 05:12:31', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\nResearchers  from KAUST Computer,Electrical and Mathematical Science and Engineering Division, worked on a technology that manufactures  more flexible silicon materials which still retains it performance.\r\n\r\nIntegrating components like sensors,data management electronics,battery,antenna into a completely complient system is not an easy task. however packaging all these discrete modules into soft substrate is extremely difficult, Also flexible printed circuits needed a conventional silicon to handle applications such as digitizing analog signal,such type of rigid modules can create uncomfortable hot spots on the body and increases device weight.\r\n\r\nThis team found a potential electronic skin application,in which a sensor containing narrow strips of aluminium foil that changes the conductivity at different bending state.This device could monitor a patients breathing pattern and other activity level,feature high_mobility Zinc oxide nanotransistor on silicon wafers thinned down lithographically to microscale dimensions for maximum flexibility.\r\n\r\nUsing 3-D printing techniques the team encapsulated the silicon chips and foils into a polymer film backed by an adhesive layer.\r\n\r\nIn addition, his colleagues found a way to make the e-sticker sensors  work in multiple applications like this pressure sensing decal can be placed on a tire to monitor it while drivig,and it can also be placed in your mattress to learn your sleeping patterns.\r\n\r\nThey used inkjet printing to write conductive wiring patterns on surfaces including paper and clothing.Custom printed decals can be attached or re-adhered to any location.\r\n\r\nThis type of decal electronics can yield a number of innovative sensor deployments,due to its robust performance and high throughput.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Flexible e-stickers as health sensors', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '55-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-01-09 05:12:31', '2017-01-09 05:12:31', '', 55, 'http://successfulindia.aypt.in/blog/55-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(61, 1, '2017-01-20 05:32:48', '2017-01-20 05:32:48', '<p style=\"text-align: center\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-65\" src=\"http://successfulindia.aypt.in/blog/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/efficient-mathematical-solver-that-run-on-graphics-processors.jpg\" alt=\"efficient-mathematical-solver-that-run-on-graphics-processors\" width=\"225\" height=\"225\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">A highly efficient mathematical solver designed to run on graphics processors gives scientists and engineers a powerful new tool for a common computational problem.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Researchers from the KAUST Extreme Computing Research Center found a technology that uses the graphics cards which are mainly used in powerful gaming computers to solve computationally intensive mathematical problems common in science and engineering applications.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">One of the most common problems in scientific and engineering computing is solving systems of multiple simultaneous equations involving thousands to millions of variables.This type of problem comes up in statistics, optimization, electrostatics, chemistry,mechanics of solid bodies on Earth and gravitational interactions among celestial bodies in space.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">In typical applications, solving such problems increases computational cost. But the solver has the potential to considerably impact both the execution time and the energy consumption required to solve the problem.Thus increasing the efficiency.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Graphics processing units (GPUs) are very energy efficient compared with standard high-performance processors because they eliminate lot of  hardware required for standard processors to execute general-purpose code.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">The key to make a more efficient solver is maximizing the trade-off between the number of processors and the memory available to temporarily store the computational data. Memory remains expensive, so finding a way to execute more computation using less memory is critical to solve the problem of computational cost.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Researchers designed a solver scheme that operates directly on data ‘in place’ without making an extra copy, this means a system twice as large can be stored in the same amount of memory.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Usually, operations on simultaneous equations are carried out by progressing sequentially over columns in the data of the matrix of values derived from the equations. Researchers converted the columns into a series of tasks on small, computationally efficient, rectangular and triangular blocks recursively carved out of the matrix. This redesigned triangular matrix-matrix multiplication implementation achieves up to eightfold acceleration compared to the speed of existing implementations.</p>', 'Efficient mathematical solver that run on graphics processors', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'efficient-mathematical-solver-that-run-on-graphics-processors', '', '', '2017-01-20 05:34:40', '2017-01-20 05:34:40', '', 0, 'http://successfulindia.aypt.in/blog/?p=61', 0, 'post', '', 0),
