(103, 1, '2017-03-13 07:06:10', '2017-03-13 07:06:10', '<strong>To the surprisingly inventive uses for banana peels :</strong>\r\n\r\nWhich include polishing silverware, leather shoes, and the leaves of house plants -- scientists have added purification of drinking water contaminated with potentially toxic metals. Their report, banana peel performs better than an array of other purification materials, appears in ACS\'s journal Industrial &amp; Engineering Chemistry Research.\r\n\r\n<strong>Substances used in the process are toxic themselves. </strong>\r\n\r\nIdustrial wastes can all put heavy metals, used in gustavo Castro and colleagues note that mining processes such as lead and copper, into waterways. Heavy metals can have adverse health and environmental effects. but Current methods of removing heavy metals Previous work has shown that some plant wastes, such as coconut fibers and peanut shells, can remove these potential toxins from water. In this report, the researchers wanted to find out whether minced banana peels could also act as water purifiers.\r\n\r\nA purification apparatus made of banana peels can be used up to 11 times without losing its metal-binding properties the team adds that banana peels are very attractive as water purifiers because of their low cost and because they don\'t have to be chemically modified in order to work.The researchers found that minced banana peel could quickly remove lead and copper from river water as well as, or better than, many other materials.', 'The second life of banana peels used in water purifier', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-second-life-of-banana-peels-used-in-water-purifier', '', '', '2017-03-13 07:06:10', '2017-03-13 07:06:10', '', 0, 'http://successfulindia.aypt.in/blog/?p=103', 0, 'post', '', 0),
