(227, 1, '2017-05-22 11:20:51', '2017-05-22 11:20:51', '<ul>\r\n 	<li></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Boolean </strong>data type consists of two possible values. They are true and false.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Number</strong> can be used both integer and fraction. It is denoted as number. It also supports hexadecimal, decimal, binary and octal literals.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>String</strong> is a sequence of characters that are enclosed with single quotes or double quotes. It is denoted as string.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Array</strong> can be stores multiple values within the single variable. It is a user defined data type. When an array is declared it allocates the memory space.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Tuples </strong>are used to store multiple fields of different types. Tuple values are called as items. They are index based. If you want to access the item from the tuple then you have to call the corresponding numeric index.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Enum</strong> is used to define as a set of named numeric constants. It is denoted as enum.</li>\r\n 	<li>If you writing an application you must need to explain the type of variables whether you don’t know. These values are dynamic. So we need opt-out checking and the values are passing through the compile time<strong>. Any</strong> has been denoted as a type any.</li>\r\n 	<li>Void is a return type function; it does not return any value.</li>\r\n 	<li>The<strong>null</strong>and the <strong>undefined</strong> data types are a source of confusion. Undefined means the variables are declared but should not be assigned. Null means the variable has set to the object its value is undefined. strictNullChecks flag, null and undefined are only assignable to void and their corresponding types. If you want to pass either a string or null or undefined, then you can use the union type.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Never</strong> represents the type of value that never occurs. If never is used as a return type that never returns anything. If never is used as the type of variable the type guards does not returns true. It is denoted as the type never.</li>\r\n 	<li><em><strong>Type assertions</strong></em>are a way to tell the compiler “trust me, I know what I’m doing. A type assertion is like a type cast, but it  performs no special checking or restructuring of data. It has no runtime impact, and is used purely done by the compiler.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Variable </strong>is acts as a container for values in program. It may be alphabets and numeric digits. It does not contain spaces and special characters except underscore and dollar sign. Variable is denoted as var keyword.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Var </strong>declarations have some <strong>scoping rules.</strong> If a variable is declared inside the if block then that variable can be access from the outside block.var declarations are accessing anywhere. It is called as var scoping or function scoping.</li>\r\n 	<li>Var declarations has some problem so let declarations are used. <strong>let</strong>declaration are done in the same way of var  When the variable is declared as let then it is called as lexical scoping or block scoping.</li>\r\n 	<li>Const declarations are same as let declaration, but the value cannot be change. It is denoted as <strong>const</strong>.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Array destructing</strong> is used to extracting multiple values where the data stored.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;', 'Type Script tutorial day 1', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '223-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-22 11:20:51', '2017-05-22 11:20:51', '', 223, 'http://successfulindia.aypt.in/blog/223-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
